{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491378"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:44:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:44:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"926"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/926"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.17,0.16,0.02,0.49]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"926"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101558"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/926"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"926"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83999"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1717"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2144"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2268"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34784"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42177"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43975"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101558"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of painless loss of vision in her left eye. She has no previous eye problems. She has a medical history of myocardial infarction one year ago for which she had two drug-eluting stents inserted. Her regular medications include clopidogrel. She does not smoke and has no known family history of eye disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious. Her pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 180/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Visual acuity in the left eye is limited to hand movements only. Ophthalmoscopic examination of the left fundus reveals retinal pallor and a cherry-red spot at the macula (Image). Urinalysis shows ++ glucose.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for her visual loss?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Embolism from a mural thrombus","Internal carotid artery occlusion","Diabetic small vessel disease","Giant cell arteritis","Embolism from a carotid plaque"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic features of central retinal artery occlusion (CRAO): sudden onset painless vision loss with characteristic fundoscopic findings of retinal pallor and a cherry-red spot at the macula. The cherry-red spot occurs because the fovea, which lacks the inner retinal layers, appears red against the surrounding pale, ischemic retina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmbolism from a carotid plaque\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of CRAO, accounting for approximately 20-40% of cases. The patient\u0027s cardiovascular risk factors (previous myocardial infarction, hypertension, and likely undiagnosed diabetes based on glucosuria) increase her risk of carotid atherosclerosis. Carotid duplex ultrasonography would be an important investigation to identify carotid stenosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmbolism from a mural thrombus\u003C/strong\u003E, typically from the heart, is a less common cause of CRAO. While this patient has a history of myocardial infarction which could predispose to mural thrombus formation, she is on clopidogrel which reduces this risk. Additionally, cardiac emboli more commonly cause branch retinal artery occlusions rather than central retinal artery occlusions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal carotid artery occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E can cause CRAO, but complete occlusion typically presents with additional neurological symptoms beyond isolated monocular vision loss. This patient has no reported neurological deficits, making isolated CRAO from carotid plaque embolism more likely than complete carotid occlusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic small vessel disease\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognized direct cause of CRAO. While the patient likely has undiagnosed diabetes (based on glucosuria), diabetic retinopathy typically causes a different pattern of retinal changes including microaneurysms, dot and blot hemorrhages, and neovascularization. Diabetes is a risk factor for atherosclerosis, which can lead to CRAO, but the small vessel disease of diabetes itself does not cause CRAO.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiant cell arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E (GCA) can cause CRAO but is less common than embolic causes. GCA typically affects patients over 50 years and presents with headache, scalp tenderness, jaw claudication, and elevated inflammatory markers. While this patient is in the appropriate age range, there is no mention of these associated symptoms, making GCA less likely than carotid embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECRAO is an ophthalmic emergency requiring urgent evaluation and management. Beyond addressing the acute vision loss, it\u0027s crucial to investigate and manage underlying cardiovascular risk factors, as CRAO can be a harbinger of stroke and other vascular events.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Central retinal artery occlusion presents with sudden painless vision loss and characteristic fundoscopic findings of retinal pallor and a cherry-red spot at the macula.","Embolism from an ipsilateral carotid plaque is the most common cause of central retinal artery occlusion.","Urgent evaluation of cardiovascular risk factors is essential in patients with retinal artery occlusion."],"references":["Hayreh, S. S., Podhajsky, P. A., \u0026 Zimmerman, M. B. (2009). Retinal artery occlusion: associated systemic and ophthalmic abnormalities. Ophthalmology, 116(10), 1928\u20131936. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ophtha.2009.03.006","Chen C, Singh G, Madike R, Cugati S. Central retinal artery occlusion: a stroke of the eye. Eye (Lond). 2024 Aug;38(12):2319-2326. doi: 10.1038/s41433-024-03029-w. Epub 2024 Mar 28. PMID: 38548943; PMCID: PMC11306586. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38548943/","Tripathy K, Shah SS, Waymack JR. Central Retinal Artery Occlusion. [Updated 2024 May 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470354/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83999"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"926"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18672"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18672"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/48c83414-633a-43c0-9f36-23c6e3768958.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/48c83414-633a-43c0-9f36-23c6e3768958.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":437}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83999"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T20:57:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T20:58:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"926"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101558"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"typ